{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"yr9120fc6u9sdac4fsjz14a","title":"Week 2","desc":"","updated":1765562906623,"created":1765457679837,"custom":{},"fname":"open-notebook.2025.12.week-2","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":".","selfContained":true,"name":"acol-dws"},"contentHash":"9a40fb06824339dde5cbc9c12feec413","links":[],"anchors":{"meeting-with-daniel-and-pierre-marie":{"type":"header","text":"Meeting with Daniel and Pierre-Marie","value":"meeting-with-daniel-and-pierre-marie","line":8,"column":0,"depth":1},"simple-error-model":{"type":"header","text":"Simple error model","value":"simple-error-model","line":9,"column":0,"depth":2},"mass-spectrometry-data":{"type":"header","text":"Mass spectrometry data","value":"mass-spectrometry-data","line":15,"column":0,"depth":2}},"children":[],"parent":"baa3hzb4zhlu5t6bvnd772z","data":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"week-2\">Week 2<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#week-2\"></a></h1>\n<h1 id=\"meeting-with-daniel-and-pierre-marie\">Meeting with Daniel and Pierre-Marie<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#meeting-with-daniel-and-pierre-marie\"></a></h1>\n<h2 id=\"simple-error-model\">Simple error model<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#simple-error-model\"></a></h2>\n<p>Currently when compiling the Markov Field, we can either target LOTUS data or the simple error model.\nI should change this so that it can both target LOTUS <em>and</em> the error model in order to add a layer of data to the model.\nThis would allow us to simulate some new data under the model and see if by adding data, the model predicts better.\n<img src=\"/acol-dws/./assets/images/IMG_20251212_171049523_HDR.jpg\"></p>\n<h2 id=\"mass-spectrometry-data\">Mass spectrometry data<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#mass-spectrometry-data\"></a></h2>\n<p>For the mass spectrometry part, we decided that we don't want to develop our own annotation tool but to use the scores of the\ndifferent existing annotation tools. </p>\n<p>The idea would be to evaluate what is the distribution of the scores of the true molecules for each annotation tool. Then in the model we feed the probability of the vector of scores given the molecule <span class=\"math math-inline\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"true\">→</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>e</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(\\overrightarrow{scores}| Molecule )</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2026em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9526em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">scores</span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3.4306em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"height:0.522em;min-width:0.888em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"400em\" height=\"0.522em\" viewBox=\"0 0 400000 522\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMaxYMin slice\"><path d=\"M0 241v40h399891c-47.3 35.3-84 78-110 128\n-16.7 32-27.7 63.7-33 95 0 1.3-.2 2.7-.5 4-.3 1.3-.5 2.3-.5 3 0 7.3 6.7 11 20\n 11 8 0 13.2-.8 15.5-2.5 2.3-1.7 4.2-5.5 5.5-11.5 2-13.3 5.7-27 11-41 14.7-44.7\n 39-84.5 73-119.5s73.7-60.2 119-75.5c6-2 9-5.7 9-11s-3-9-9-11c-45.3-15.3-85\n-40.5-119-75.5s-58.3-74.8-73-119.5c-4.7-14-8.3-27.3-11-40-1.3-6.7-3.2-10.8-5.5\n-12.5-2.3-1.7-7.5-2.5-15.5-2.5-14 0-21 3.7-21 11 0 2 2 10.3 6 25 20.7 83.3 67\n 151.7 139 205zm0 0v40h399900v-40z\"></path></svg></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ec</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></span>. </p>\n<p><img src=\"/acol-dws/./assets/images/IMG_20251212_171139756_HDR.jpg\"></p>","noteIndex":{"id":"3rbfqqbp7pwbkdcrgc97u7l","title":"Anticipated Chemistry of Life","desc":"","updated":1727785927929,"created":1671985562294,"custom":{"nav_order":0,"permalink":"/"},"fname":"root","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":".","selfContained":true,"name":"acol-dws"},"contentHash":"f1947bd87c177e8ee5739c542c5dc574","links":[],"anchors":{"welcome-to-the-dendron-of-the-anticipated-chemistry-of-life":{"type":"header","text":"Welcome to the Dendron of the Anticipated Chemistry of Life","value":"welcome-to-the-dendron-of-the-anticipated-chemistry-of-life","line":8,"column":0,"depth":1}},"children":["l03fwlci5f5rdpot3v7oli6","zxc3pre92d542wg70hmdhgl","yl3j0gor5m5od4j1y5vbxih","jqc7nvrtk6bmno394fcuw1u","ghtzzi5buglirob2qidl5eo","9k3x188zfa3yookx15exx47","5h5hzto7ygkv874tw74ywks"],"parent":null,"data":{},"body":"\n# Welcome to the Dendron of the Anticipated Chemistry of Life\n\nThis dendron has the purpose to serve as a laboratory notebook for my PhD thesis. It will contain all the notes that I will take during my research as well as some results of the experiments and models that I will develop and test.\n"},"collectionChildren":null,"customHeadContent":null,"config":{"versio